properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. Snow and blowing snow in store for Monday. A Pacific low pressure system will develop in the Gulf of Alaska tonight and then cross the Alaska Panhandle on Monday. It will track east along the 60th parallel to pass just south of Whitehorse late Monday afternoon and close to Watson Lake by late Monday evening. Snow is forecast to develop tonight and persist all day Monday. Total snowfall amounts of 15 to 20 cm are likely through Monday night. In addition, south winds will develop Monday morning and then shift to strong northwest winds Monday evening. This will cause local blowing snow and poor visibilities. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of very cold wind chills continues. The coldest wind chill values will be between minus 55 and minus 60. These very cold wind chill values will persist until Monday night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow and blowing snow in store for Monday. A Pacific low pressure system will develop in the Gulf of Alaska tonight and then cross the Haines-Skagway Roads on Monday. Snow is forecast to develop tonight and persist all day Monday. Total snowfall amounts of 20 cm or more are likely through Monday evening. In addition, strong south winds will develop by Monday morning and then shift to strong north winds Monday evening. This will cause widespread blowing snow and poor visibilities. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
